            desc: "France's parliament finally passed the 2026 Budget Bill in early February, after two no-confidence motions against PM Sebastien Lecornu's government failed to gain majority support.",
            content: "<p>After months of political deadlock, France's parliament finally passed the 2026 Budget Bill in early February 2026, following the failure of two no-confidence motions filed by the opposition against Prime Minister Sebastien Lecornu's government. This passage marked an important political victory for President Emmanuel Macron, who had previously lost four prime ministers in a short period due to prolonged budget crises.</p><p>The new budget targets reducing the fiscal deficit to 5% of GDP by end of 2026, down from around 5.8% the previous year, with a long-term plan to reduce the deficit to 2.8% of GDP by 2029. To achieve this, the government raised several corporate taxes and cut public spending across sectors, while still allocating a defense budget increase of about $7.6 million amid geopolitical pressure in Europe.</p><p>Opposition from both left and right wings filed two separate no-confidence motions accusing the government of sacrificing public welfare for fiscal consolidation. However, both motions failed to gain the required majority in the Assemblée Nationale, giving some breathing room to Lecornu's fragile coalition government.</p><p>Despite the budget's passage, economists warn France's political stability remains fragile given a fragmented parliament without a clear majority since the 2024 legislative elections. Analysts from several financial institutions view this budget passage more as a short-term solution than a structural resolution to France's prolonged fiscal crisis.</p>",
